            <ArticleTitle>A Simplified Basis for Bell-Kochen-Specker Theorems.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>2611-2613</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>We show that a reduced form of the structural requirements for deterministic hidden variables used in Bell-Kochen-Specker theorems is already sufficient for the no-go results. Those requirements are captured by the following principle: an observable takes a spectral value <i>x</i> if and only if the spectral projector associated with <i>x</i> takes the value 1. We show that the &quot;only if&quot; part of this condition suffices. The proof identifies an important structural feature behind the no-go results; namely, if <i>at least</i> one projector is assigned the value 1 in any resolution of the identity, then <i>at mos</i>t one is.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
